SIMPLE: oration
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oration
<hw>O*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos><ety>[L.
<ets>oratio</ets>, fr. <ets>orare</ets> to speak, utter, pray. See
<er>Oral</er>, <er>Orison</er>.]</ety> <def>An elaborate discourse,
delivered in public, treating an important subject in a formal and
dignified manner; especially, a discourse having reference to some
special occasion, as a funeral, an anniversary, a celebration, or the
like; -- distinguished from an argument in court, a popular harangue, a
sermon, a lecture, etc.; <as>as, Webster's <ex>oration</ex> at Bunker
Hill</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lord archbishop . . . made a long <qex>oration</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Address; speech. See <er>Harangue</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oration</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Oration
<hw>O*ra"tion</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To deliver an oration.</def>
<rj><au>Donne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Orator</ent>⟦br⟧
